6562182605267, 0.004742209333926439, 0.01734091527760029, -0.03887195885181427, -0.00929331500083208, -0.037994299083948135, 0.01586870662868023, -0.003116056090220809, -0.01186967920511961, 0.03717326000332832, 0.00439539086073637, -0.006858508568257093, -0.0033673224970698357, -0.028495723381638527, 0.03904183208942413, -0.038362350314855576, -0.005966690368950367, 0.006872664671391249, 0.01687377132475376, -0.035332996398210526, -0.03810754418373108, -0.011480392888188362, 0.012520847842097282, 0.01810532994568348, 0.020313642919063568, 0.002093296032398939, -0.018416758626699448, 0.008118378929793835, -0.0181619543582201, -0.029047802090644836, 0.0022826306521892548, 0.0007719361456111073, 0.015005199238657951, 0.019591694697737694, -0.017510784789919853, 0.061549630016088486, -0.0037159102503210306, -0.01681714877486229, 0.008380262181162834, -0.01165734138339758, 0.05161222442984581, 0.013164939358830452]], "input": ["\"MAKE VS. BUY DECISIONS\":\"Make vs. Buy Decisions involve calculating the financial effect of outsourcing the manufacture of a particular component. This includes determining the costs saved if in-house production ceases and comparing this with the costs of buying the component from an external supplier.\"", "\"SPLIT-OFF POINT\":\"The split-off point is the stage in the production process where joint products can be recognized as separate products. Costs incurred up to this point are considered common costs.\"", "\"INCREMENTAL REVENUE\":\"INCREMENTAL REVENUE\" refers to the additional revenue generated from a new activity or decision, such as further processing a product beyond the split-off point. It is a key factor in making further processing decisions.", "\"VARIABLE COST\":\"Variable cost\" refers to expenses that vary directly with the level of production or sales volume. These costs include items such as raw materials, direct labor, and sales commissions. In the context of outsourcing, services becoming a variable cost is considered an advantage. Specifically, the variable cost per customer is $1.20.", "\"CORE COMPETENCIES\":\"Core competencies are the main strengths or strategic advantages of a business. Outsourcing allows management to focus on these core competencies.\"", "\"COMMON COST\":", "\"BREAKEVEN POINT\":The breakeven point is the level of activity at which neither a profit nor a loss is made. It is a measure of the lowest activity level at which the activity is viable, where total contribution equals total fixed costs. At this point, total sales equal total costs, ensuring that the company makes neither profit nor loss.", "\"CONTRIBUTION\":\"Contribution\" is the amount remaining from sales revenue after deducting variable costs, which contributes to covering fixed costs and generating profit. It is the difference between sales revenue and variable costs. For Division M, the contribution on external sales is $80 per unit. Contribution refers to earnings from sales after deducting variable costs and is computed by deducting variable costs from revenue. The funds available from contribution are used to cover fixed costs, and any excess over fixed costs is considered profit.", "\"CONTRIBUTION TO SALES RATIO\":The \"Contribution to Sales Ratio\" is calculated by dividing the contribution per unit by the selling price per unit. This ratio is used to determine the profitability of products in both single and multi-product situations.", "\"TARGET PROFIT OR REVENUE\":\"Target profit or revenue is calculated by determining the sales volume needed to achieve a specific profit level. This involves adding the target profit to the fixed costs and dividing by the contribution per unit.\"", "\"BREAKEVEN CHART\":A breakeven chart is a graphical representation that shows the point at which total costs and total revenue are equal. It plots revenue and costs against volume, with the intersection of the total cost and revenue lines indicating the breakeven point. This chart helps in visualizing the relationship between costs, revenue, and profit at different levels of activity.", "\"PROFIT-VOLUME CHART\":\"A profit-volume (PV) chart presents the same information as a breakeven chart but emphasizes profits and losses at different activity levels. It requires information on profit or loss at any level of sales and total fixed costs.\"", "\"SIMPLIFYING ASSUMPTIONS OF CVP ANALYSIS\":\"SIMPLIFYING ASSUMPTIONS OF CVP ANALYSIS\"\n\nThe main limitations of CVP (Cost-Volume-Profit) analysis for planning and decision-making stem from the necessary simplifying assumptions. These assumptions include the following: fixed costs remain constant, the variable cost per unit remains constant, and the selling price remains constant. Additionally, CVP analysis assumes that total cost behaves as a strictly linear semi-variable cost, unit selling prices do not change with volume, costs and income are matched, levels of efficiency and productivity do not change, and there is either only a single product or a constant sales mix of more than one product. These assumptions are critical for the analysis but can limit its applicability in more complex, real-world scenarios.", "\"EXAMPLE OF DEPENDENCE ON SALES VOLUME\":\"Company A knows the sales price for product X will be around $50, and its variable costs are approximately $30. The contribution per unit is $20. With annual fixed costs of $200,000, Company A needs to sell 10,000 units to break even.\"", "\"QUIZ: BREAKEVEN CHART\":\"This quiz involves drawing a breakeven chart for a product called gamma, with a selling price of $100 per unit, variable cost of $20 per unit, and fixed costs of $1,000,000 per year. The breakeven level of sales is determined to be 12,500 units.\"", "\"CVP ANALYSIS\":"], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}